# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: raspberry-pi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The operating system is compatible with all Raspberry Pi models except the Raspberry Pi Pico microcontroller.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] It is available in several configurations: a standard edition, a "Lite" version without a desktop environment, and a "Full" version that includes additional software such as LibreOffice and Wolfram Mathematica.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The operating system is available as a free download and can be installed using the official Raspberry Pi Imager utility.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] It is also sold preloaded on official microSD cards.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Raspbian was first developed by Mike Thompson and Peter Green as an independent and unofficial port of Debian to the Raspberry Pi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The first build was released on 15 July 2012.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] As the Raspberry Pi had no officially provided operating system at the time, the Raspberry Pi Foundation built on the work by the Raspbian project and began producing and releasing their own operating system images of the software.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The Foundation's first release of Raspbian, which now referred both to the community project as well as the official operating system, was announced on 10 September 2013.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] On 28 May 2020, the Raspberry Pi Foundation announced a beta 64-bit version.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] However, this version was not based on Raspbian, instead taking its user space software from Debian.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] When the Foundation did not want to use the name Raspbian to refer to software that was not based on the Raspbian project, the name of the officially provided operating system images was changed to Raspberry Pi OS.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] This change was also carried over to the 32-bit images that they distributed, though it continued to be based on Raspbian.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The 64-bit version of Raspberry Pi OS was officially released on 2 February 2022.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The Raspberry Pi OS user interface is optimized for Raspberry Pi hardware and tuned to have low base memory requirements, aiming to deliver a lightweight, fast, and energy-efficient desktop experience.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] It is built on the Wayland display protocol, using labwc as its compositing manager, which is based on wlroots, a modular Wayland implementation that underpins several other compositors.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The operating system previously used the X Window System.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] A transition to Wayland began with the Bullseye release in 2021, which introduced the mutter window manager to support both X and Wayland environments.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In the Bookworm release of 2023, wayfire was adopted as a dedicated Wayland compositor.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] However, performance issues on older Raspberry Pi models prompted a search for a more suitable alternative.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In 2024, developers ultimately selected labwc, a lightweight compositor that better matched the hardware's capabilities.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Following collaboration and extensive optimization, labwc now offers performance comparable to X across all models, and Raspberry Pi OS now defaults to Wayland.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The interface is designed to feel familiar to users of macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] It provides a traditional desktop environment with a top menu bar that includes an application menu, shortcuts to frequently used programs, and system controls such as Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, volume, and clock.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Raspberry Pi OS originally included the Epiphany web browser, but transitioned to Chromium in 2016.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Firefox was added as an additional pre-installed browser option in 2023.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The included browsers come with uBlock, an ad-blocking extension, and h264ify, an extension that makes YouTube serve videos using the H.264 codec which is supported by the Raspberry Pi's hardware acceleration.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] As of May 2025, other pre-installed applications includes Geany, ImageMagick, Thonny, VNC Viewer and VLC media player.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] As of May 2025, installations with the full suite of recommended software includes Claws Mail, Firebird database server, KiCad, LibreOffice, Java, Scratch, and Wolfram Mathematica, and additional font packages.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Software can be installed via the APT (Advanced Package Tool) command-line interface, or through graphical front-ends such as the included Add/Remove Software tool, or by using third-party app stores like Pi-Apps.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] According to Raspberry Pi Imager usage statistics, Raspberry Pi OS accounted for 67% of all operating system downloads for the Raspberry Pi in May 2025, followed by Ubuntu at 9%.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In a 2015 review, Jesse Smith of *DistroWatch* found that while Raspbian was not well-suited for heavier desktop workloads, it provided a functional experience with its lightweight environment.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] He noted that the system was responsive when running a modest number of applications, but struggled with more resource-intensive software such as LibreOffice or Firefox.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In a January 2024 review for *Ars Technica*, Andrew Cunningham tested Raspberry Pi OS version 5 on a Pi 5 with 8 GB of RAM and found it functional for general-purpose desktop use, but with notable limitations.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] While it handled basic tasks like writing, web browsing, and audio editing well, the OS lacked modern conveniences such as window snapping, a notification center, refined window borders, and smooth multi-monitor performance.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Its software ecosystem was also constrained by limited native app availability for ARM Linux, often requiring users to rely on web-based versions of services like Slack, Zoom, and Dropbox.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In January 2021, the Raspberry Pi OS package `raspberrypi-sys-mods` added a Microsoft GPG encryption key and repository configuration to the APT package manager, enabling easier installation of Visual Studio Code, a source code editor.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] As a result, the system contacted Microsoft's servers during update checks, prompting concerns among users due to privacy considerations and Microsoft's once-adversarial history with the open source software community.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The repository configuration was later removed.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Each variant is available in both 32-bit and 64-bit versions.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] A "legacy" branch has been available since December 2021.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] It is based on the previous stable release of Debian, allowing for continued use of older software while still receiving security and hardware support updates.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] All standard variants (Lite, with desktop, and with desktop and recommended software) are offered in this legacy form.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] New major versions of Debian are released every two years, typically in the summer of odd-numbered years (e.g., 2023, 2025, 2027).
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Raspberry Pi OS ports of each new Debian release generally follow a few months later, usually in the fall.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Raspberry Pi OS can be purchased pre-installed on a microSD card or downloaded as a `.img` disk image file to be written to an SD card or other media.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Official documentation recommends a minimum of 16 GB for the Lite version and at least 32 GB for versions with a desktop environment.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] The **Raspberry Pi Imager** utility was introduced in March 2020 to simplify the installation of a disk image file onto an SD card or other media.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] Available for macOS, Raspberry Pi OS, Ubuntu, and Windows, it allows users to download and write the disk image file in a single application.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-os] In addition to Raspberry Pi OS, the utility supports a variety of third-party operating systems.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi was originally created to help teach computer science in schools, but gained popularity for many other uses due to its low cost, compact size, and flexibility.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] It is now used in areas such as industrial automation, robotics, home automation, IoT devices, and hobbyist projects.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The company's products range from simple microcontrollers to computers that the company markets as being powerful enough to be used as a general purpose PC.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Computers are built around a custom designed system on a chip and offer features such as HDMI video/audio output, USB ports, wireless networking, GPIO pins, and up to 16 GB of RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Storage is typically provided via microSD cards.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In 2015, the Raspberry Pi surpassed the ZX Spectrum as the best-selling British computer of all time.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] As of March 2025, 68 million units had been sold.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Foundation was established in 2008 by a group including Eben Upton, in response to a noticeable decline in both the number and skill level of students applying to study computer science at the University of Cambridge Computer Laboratory.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The foundation's goal was to create a low-cost computer to help rekindle interest in programming among schoolchildren.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This mission was inspired by the aims of the BBC Micro computer of the early 1980s, which was developed by Acorn Computers as part of a BBC initiative to promote computer literacy in UK schools.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The names "Model A" and "Model B" were chosen as a deliberate homage to the BBC Micro.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The name "Raspberry Pi" combines the fruit-themed naming convention used by early computer companies with a nod to the Python programming language.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The first prototypes resembled small USB sticks.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] By August 2011, fifty functionally complete "alpha" boards were produced for testing, with demonstrations showing them running a Debian-based desktop and handling 1080p video playback.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In late 2011, twenty-five "beta" boards were finalized, and to generate publicity before the official launch, ten of these were auctioned on eBay in early 2012.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The first commercial Raspberry Pi, the Model B, was launched on 29 February 2012, with an initial price of $35.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Demand far exceeded expectations, causing the websites of the two initial licensed distributors, Premier Farnell and RS Components, to crash from high traffic.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Initial batches sold out almost immediately, with one distributor reporting over 100,000 pre-orders on the first day.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The lower-cost $25 Model A followed on 4 February 2013.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi did not ship with a pre-installed operating system.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] While ports of RISC OS 5 and Fedora Linux were available, a port of Debian called Raspbian quickly became the standard.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Released in July 2012, it was optimized to leverage the Raspberry Pi's floating-point unit, offering significant performance gains.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi quickly endorsed it as the official recommended OS, and by September 2013, the company assumed leadership of Raspbian's development.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In 2012, the Foundation restructured, creating Raspberry Pi (Trading) Ltd. to handle engineering and commercial activities, with Eben Upton as its CEO.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This allowed the Raspberry Pi Foundation to focus solely on its charitable and educational mission.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi (Trading) Ltd. was renamed Raspberry Pi Ltd. in 2021.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In June 2024, the company went public on the London Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol RPI, becoming Raspberry Pi Holdings.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Following the launch, the first units reached buyers in April 2012.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] To address overwhelming demand and initial supply chain issues, the Foundation ramped up production to 4,000 units per day by July.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The first batch of 10,000 boards was produced in factories located in Taiwan and China.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A significant strategic shift occurred in September 2012, when manufacturing began moving to a Sony factory in Pencoed, Wales.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] During this period, the hardware was also refined: the Model B Revision 2.0 board was announced with minor corrections, and in October, its included RAM was doubled to 512 MB.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The post-launch period focused heavily on software and ecosystem development.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In August 2012, the Foundation enabled hardware-accelerated H.264 video encoding and began selling licenses for MPEG-2 and VC-1 codecs.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A major milestone for the open-source community occurred in October 2012, when the Foundation released the Videocore IV graphics driver as free software.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] While the claim of it being the first fully open-source ARM SoC driver was debated, the move was widely praised.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This effort culminated in February 2014 with the release of full documentation for the graphics core and a complete source release of the graphics stack under a 3-clause BSD license.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In 2014, the Raspberry Pi product line began to diversify.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] April saw the release of the Compute Module, a miniature Raspberry Pi in a small form factor designed for industrial and embedded applications, which would soon become the largest market for the computers.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In July the Model B+ was released with a refined design featuring additional USB ports and a more efficient board layout that established the form factor for future models.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A smaller, cheaper ($20) Model A+ was released in November.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A significant leap in performance came in February 2015 with the Raspberry Pi 2, which featured a 900 MHz quad-core CPU and 1 GB of RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Following its release, the price of the Model B+ was lowered to $25, a move some observers linked to the emergence of lower-priced competitors.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Zero, launched in November 2015, radically redefined the entry point for computing at a price of just $5.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In February 2016, the Raspberry Pi 3 marked another major milestone by integrating a 64-bit processor, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The product line continued to expand with the wireless-enabled Raspberry Pi Zero W (February 2017), the faster Raspberry Pi 3B+ (March 2018), Raspberry Pi 3A+ (November 2018), and Compute Module 3+ (January 2019).
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 4, launched in June 2019, represented another major performance leap with a faster processor, up to 8 GB of RAM, dual-monitor support, and USB 3.0 ports.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A compute module version (CM4) launched in October 2020.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This era saw further diversification with the Raspberry Pi 400 (a computer integrated into a keyboard) in November 2020, and the Raspberry Pi Pico in January 2021.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pico, based on the in-house designed RP2040 chip, marked the company's first entry into the low-cost microcontroller market.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W, introduced in 2021, featured a faster processor, providing a significant performance boost while maintaining the low-cost, compact form factor.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The global chip shortage starting in 2020, as well as an uptake in demand starting in early 2021, notably affected the Raspberry Pi, causing significant availability issues from that time onward.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The company explained its approach to the shortages in 2021, and April 2022, explaining that it was prioritising business and industrial customers.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 5 was released in October 2023, featuring an upgraded CPU and GPU, up to 16 GB of RAM, a PCIe interface for fast peripherals and an in-house designed southbridge chip.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Updated versions of the Compute Module (CM5) and keyboard computer (Pi 500, Pi 500+) based on the Pi 5's architecture were subsequently announced.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Pico 2, released in 2024, introduced the RP2350 microcontroller, featuring two Hazard3 RISC-V and two ARM Cortex-M33 cores, any two of which may be selected at boot time, 520 KB of RAM, and 4 MB of flash memory.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi expanded its artificial intelligence focused hardware ecosystem with the release of the Raspberry Pi AI Camera, based on Sony's IMX500 Intelligent Vision Sensor.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The product integrated on-sensor neural network inference, enabling edge-based computer vision applications when paired with Raspberry Pi computers.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The company also introduced the Raspberry Pi AI HAT+, incorporating a Hailo neural processing unit (NPU) to accelerate machine learning workloads on the Raspberry Pi 5 platform.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The accessory was positioned for high-performance edge inference use cases, including industrial automation and embedded AI systems.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] During the same period, Raspberry Pi announced updated keyboard-integrated desktop models derived from the Raspberry Pi 5 architecture.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] These revisions included expanded memory configurations and enhanced storage options, continuing the company's development of compact, integrated desktop computing systems.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi's sales demonstrated remarkable growth.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The one-millionth Pi was sold by October 2013, a figure that doubled just a month later.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] By February 2016, sales reached eight million units, surpassing the ZX Spectrum as the best-selling British computer of all time.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Sales hit ten million in September 2016, thirty million by December 2019, and forty million by May 2021.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] As of its tenth anniversary in February 2022, a total of 46 million Raspberry Pis had been sold.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] There are five main series of Raspberry Pi computers, each with multiple generations.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most models feature a Broadcom system on a chip (SoC) with an integrated ARM-based central processing unit (CPU) and an on-chip graphics processing unit (GPU).
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The exception is the Pico series, a microcontroller which uses the RP2040, a custom-designed SoC with an ARM-compatible CPU but no GPU.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The flagship Raspberry Pi series, often referred to simply as "Raspberry Pi", offers high-performance hardware, a full Linux operating system, and a variety of common ports in a compact form factor roughly the size of a credit card.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Keyboard Computer series combines Raspberry Pi board and a keyboard into a keyboard computer form factor, providing a self-contained Linux-based desktop system.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Zero is a series of compact, low-cost, and low-power single-board computers that provide basic functionality and Linux compatibility for embedded and minimalist computing applications.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pico is a series of compact microcontroller boards based on Raspberry Pi-designed chips.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Unlike other models, they do not run Linux or support removable storage, and are instead programmed by flashing binaries to onboard flash memory.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The **Compute Module** (CM) series delivers Raspberry Pi's flagship hardware in a compact form for industrial and embedded applications, omitting onboard ports and GPIO headers in favour of a carrier board interface.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Compute Modules are offered in one of two formats: a board matching the physical dimensions of a DDR2 SO-DIMM RAM module (though electrically incompatible with standard SO-DIMM sockets) and a smaller board with dual 100-pin high-density connectors that enables additional interfaces.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Since its introduction, Raspberry Pi hardware has been designed to provide low-cost computing platforms.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The founders intended it to be an affordable and accessible system by making it compatible with widely available second-hand peripherals, such as televisions for displays, USB input devices, and cellphone chargers for power.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Over time, the hardware has expanded to support both advanced configurations and ultra-low-cost variants.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The company has committed to keeping its single-board computer products in production for at least ten years, longer than typical consumer electronics.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] It also publishes guaranteed minimum manufacturing end dates.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] These policies are intended to support the use of its products in industrial and OEM applications that require long-term availability.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] For example, the original Raspberry Pi Model 1B, introduced in 2012, remained in production as of 2025.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi has undergone multiple hardware revisions, with changes in processor type, memory capacity, networking features, and peripheral support.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] All models include a processor, memory, and various input/output interfaces on a single circuit board.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most include an HDMI output, USB ports, and a GPIO (general-purpose input/output) header.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Networking capabilities vary by model, with later versions featuring integrated Wi-Fi and Bluetooth.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Storage is typically provided via a microSD card, with newer models supporting USB or PCIe-based boot options.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi models use a range of system on a chip (SoC) designs, developed in partnership with Arm and Broadcom.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Each generation has introduced improvements in CPU architecture, clock speed, graphics, and overall performance.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The original Raspberry Pi and the Pi Zero use the Broadcom BCM2835, featuring a single-core 32-bit ARM11 CPU and a VideoCore IV GPU.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The CPU is clocked at 700 MHz on the original Pi and 1 GHz on the Zero and Zero W.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 2 introduced the BCM2836 with a 900 MHz quad-core 32-bit Cortex-A7 CPU, while later revisions used the 64-bit BCM2837 with Cortex-A53 cores.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 3 retained the BCM2837, increasing the CPU clock to 1.2–1.4 GHz depending on the model.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pi Zero 2 uses the RP3A0, a system in a package (SiP) combining the quad-core Cortex-A53 processor clocked at 1 GHz with 512 MB of RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 4 introduced the BCM2711, a 64-bit SoC with a quad-core Cortex-A72 CPU and VideoCore VI GPU.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Clock speeds were initially 1.5 GHz and later increased to 1.8 GHz.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 5 uses the BCM2712, featuring a quad-core Cortex-A76 CPU at 2.4 GHz, an 800 MHz VideoCore VII GPU, and a separate RP1 southbridge chip designed in-house.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi has also developed its own chips outside of its partnership with Broadcom.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi Pico uses the RP2040, featuring dual-core 32-bit Cortex-M0+ processors running at 133 MHz and 264 kB of on-chip RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pico 2 uses the RP2350, featuring two Cortex-M33 and two Hazard3 RISC-V CPU cores, any two of which may be selected at boot, running at 150 MHz, with 520 kB of RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most Raspberry Pi models support user-configurable overclocking through the system configuration file.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] More recent models feature dynamic frequency scaling, adjusting CPU speed based on workload to balance performance and thermal output.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This behavior, while similar to overclocking, is part of the default power management system.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] If the CPU temperature exceeds 85 °C (185 °F) or if undervoltage is detected, performance is throttled automatically.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] For sustained high-performance workloads, additional cooling—such as a heat sink or fan—may be required.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The original Raspberry Pi Model B was equipped with 512 MB of random-access memory (RAM), which, like later models, shares memory between the CPU and GPU.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] All Raspberry Pi boards support dynamic memory allocation between these components, allowing the system to adjust the division based on workload or user configuration.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The original Model A included 256 MB of RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Subsequent models introduced increased memory capacities.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pi 2B and 3 B/B+ models feature 1 GB of RAM, while the smaller 1A+ and 3A+ models have 512 MB.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pi Zero and Zero 2 W also include 512 MB.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pi 4 is available with 1, 2, 3, 4, or 8 GB of RAM, and the Pi 5 expands this further with options for 1, 2, 4, 8, or 16 GB of RAM, the highest capacity offered to date.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] On 1 April 2026, Raspberry Pi announced a 3 GB version of the Raspberry Pi 4 due to the increasing cost of LPDDR4 RAM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The PCB was redesigned to use two 1.5 GB chips, which are cheaper and in greater supply.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Storage is typically provided via a microSD card, though some Compute Modules offer onboard eMMC flash.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Newer models support USB booting, and the Pi 5 includes support for NVMe SSDs over PCIe.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The original Model A and Model B uses a full-sized SD card slot.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Boards also include USB ports for peripherals such as keyboards, mice, and storage devices.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi devices support both digital and analog video output across various resolutions.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Early models featured a full-size HDMI port and an RCA connector for analog composite video output.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Later boards removed the RCA jack but retained analog output via the 3.5 mm TRRS jack or dedicated solder points.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] According to the Raspberry Pi Foundation, analog support helps maintain accessibility in developing countries.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] To accommodate the addition of features on the compact boards, video connectors have shrunk across models.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pi Zero series uses a mini-HDMI connector, while the Pi 4 and 5 use dual micro-HDMI ports.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This change enables support for multiple displays: the Pi 4 can drive two 4K displays at 30 Hz or one at 60 Hz, while the Pi 5 improves on this with support for two 4K displays at 60 Hz.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Older Raspberry Pi models support common display resolutions such as 720p and 1080p by default, with some capable of higher resolutions depending on hardware and configuration.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In some cases, older hardware can output in 4K, though performance may be poor.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most Raspberry Pi models include a 40-pin connector known as the GPIO (general-purpose input/output) header, although only some of the pins are dedicated to GPIO functions.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The header, designated as J8, uses a consistent pinout across models.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The header supplies 3.3 V and 5 V power along with various multiplexed, low-speed interfaces, including UART, SPI, I²C, I²S, and PCM.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] GPIO pins can be configured as either inputs or outputs.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] When set as an output, a pin can drive a high (3.3 V) or low (0 V) signal.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] When configured as an input, it can read a high (3.3 V) or low (0 V) voltage level.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The original Raspberry Pi 1 Model A and B include only the first 26 pins of this header.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] On some Pi Zero models, the header is unpopulated, but solderable through-holes are provided.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Pico models feature a unique layout with unpopulated through-holes and a castellated edge, allowing it to be surface-mounted as a module.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Compute Module boards do not include GPIO headers but instead expose GPIO signals through their board connectors.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Networking capabilities differ by model.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Model B and B+ include an Ethernet port.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Starting with the Raspberry Pi 3, most models come with built-in WiFi and Bluetooth.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 3B+ adds faster Ethernet and dual-band WiFi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 4 and 5 offer full gigabit Ethernet.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The "A" models and the Pi Zero series do not have Ethernet ports, and built-in wireless support is optional.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A USB adapter may be used for wired or wireless connections.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Headless Raspberry Pi configurations may experience intermittent network connectivity issues, often attributed to default WiFi power management settings.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] These issues are typically addressable through configuration changes.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Some Raspberry Pi models, like the Zero, 1A, 3A+, and 4, can act like a USB device (via the USB On-The-Go protocol) when plugged into another computer.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This lets them work as gadgets such as a virtual keyboard, network adapter, or serial device.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Many newer models can also start up (or "boot") directly from a USB drive, without needing a microSD card.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This feature is not available on older models like the original Raspberry Pi, Pi Zero, or early versions of the Pi 2.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most Raspberry Pi models do not include a built-in real-time clock, which means they rely on an internet connection to set the correct time with the Network Time Protocol when they start up.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] If there is no connection, the time must be set manually; otherwise, the system assumes no time has passed since it was last used.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Add-on clock modules are available for situations where accurate timekeeping is needed without internet access.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi 5 is the first model to include a built-in clock which uses a battery to keep time when powered off.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] plus the same specific functions, HAT, and an additional 4× UART, 4× SPI, and 4× I2C connectors.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] 5. via on-board 3-port USB hub; one USB port internally connected to the Ethernet port.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] 6. via on-board 5-port USB hub; one USB port internally connected to the Ethernet port.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The recommended operating system is Raspberry Pi OS, a Debian-based Linux distribution optimized for Raspberry Pi hardware and tuned to have low base memory requirements.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] It is available in both 32-bit and 64-bit versions and comes in several editions: a standard edition, a "Lite" version without a desktop environment, and a "Full" version that includes a comprehensive suite of software.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi OS can be purchased pre-installed on a microSD card, or downloaded and installed using Raspberry Pi Imager, a utility introduced in March 2020 to simplify the installation of operating systems onto SD cards and other media for Raspberry Pi devices.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Available for macOS, Raspberry Pi OS, Ubuntu, and Windows, Imager allows users to download and write operating system disk images within a single application.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In addition to Raspberry Pi OS, the utility supports a variety of third-party operating systems, including Alpine Linux, Arch Linux ARM, Armbian, Emteria.OS (Android based), FreedomBox, Kali Linux, LibreELEC, RetroPie, RISC OS, SatNOGS, Ubuntu, and Arm versions of Windows 10 IoT Core and version 11.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The Raspberry Pi uses official firmware that is proprietary, meaning its source code is not publicly available, but the binary blob can be freely redistributed.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] An experimental open-source alternative to the official firmware is also available.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Although limited in functionality, it demonstrates that it is possible to start the Raspberry Pi's ARM processor cores and boot a basic version of the Linux kernel without relying on the proprietary components.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] This is significant for developers and advocates who aim to build fully open systems.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi systems use Broadcom's VideoCore GPU, which requires a proprietary firmware binary blob to be loaded at boot.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Initially, the supporting software stack was entirely proprietary, though parts of the code were later released.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Most driver functionality remains within the proprietary GPU firmware, accessed via closed-source runtime libraries such as OpenMAX IL, OpenGL ES, and OpenVG.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] These libraries interface with a kernel-space open-source driver, which in turn communicates with the proprietary GPU firmware.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Applications use OpenMAX IL for video, OpenGL ES for 3D graphics, and OpenVG for 2D graphics, with all graphics libraries making use of the closed-source EGL interface.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] In February 2020, Raspberry Pi announced the development of a Vulkan graphics driver.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] A working prototype demonstrated high performance in Quake III Arena on a Raspberry Pi 3B+ later that year.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] On 24 November 2020, Raspberry Pi 4's Vulkan driver was declared conformant.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Raspberry Pi offers several official camera modules that connect via the Camera Serial Interface.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] These modules are used for photography, video capture, and machine vision applications.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Official Raspberry Pi HATs (Hardware Attached on Top) and expansion boards extend the functionality of Raspberry Pi computers.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] The HAT standard was introduced in July 2014.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p01] Many boards use an EEPROM for automatic configuration.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Technology writer Glyn Moody described the project in May 2011 as a "potential BBC Micro 2.0", not by replacing PC compatible machines but by supplementing them.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In March 2012 Stephen Pritchard echoed the BBC Micro successor sentiment in *ITPRO*.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Alex Hope, co-author of the Next Gen report, is hopeful that the computer will engage children with the excitement of programming.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Co-author Ian Livingstone suggested that the BBC could be involved in building support for the device, possibly branding it as the BBC Nano.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The Centre for Computing History strongly supports the Raspberry Pi project, feeling that it could "usher in a new era".
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Before release, the board was showcased by ARM's CEO Warren East at an event in Cambridge outlining Google's ideas to improve UK science and technology education.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Harry Fairhead, however, suggests that more emphasis should be put on improving the educational software available on existing hardware, using tools such as MIT App Inventor to return programming to schools, rather than adding new hardware choices.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Simon Rockman, writing in a *ZDNet* blog, was of the opinion that teens will have "better things to do", despite what happened in the 1980s.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In October 2012, the Raspberry Pi won T3's Innovation of the Year award, and futurist Mark Pesce cited a (borrowed) Raspberry Pi as the inspiration for his ambient device project MooresCloud.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In June 2017, Raspberry Pi won the Royal Academy of Engineering MacRobert Award.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Clusters of hundreds of Raspberry Pis have been used for testing programs destined for supercomputers.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The Raspberry Pi community was described by Jamie Ayre of FOSS software company AdaCore as one of the most exciting parts of the project.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Community blogger Russell Davis said that the community strength allows the Foundation to concentrate on documentation and teaching.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The community developed a fanzine around the platform called *The MagPi* which in 2015, was handed over to Raspberry Pi (Trading) Ltd by its volunteers to be continued in-house.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] A series of community *Raspberry Jam* events have been held across the UK and around the world.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] As of January 2012, enquiries about the board in the United Kingdom have been received from both state and private schools, with around five times as much interest from the latter.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] It is hoped that businesses will sponsor purchases for less advantaged schools.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The CEO of Premier Farnell said that the government of a country in the Middle East has expressed interest in providing a board to every schoolgirl, to enhance her employment prospects.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In 2014, the Raspberry Pi Foundation hired a number of its community members including ex-teachers and software developers to launch a set of free learning resources for its website.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The Foundation also started a teacher training course called Picademy with the aim of helping teachers prepare for teaching the new computing curriculum using the Raspberry Pi in the classroom.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In 2018, NASA launched the *JPL Open Source Rover Project*, which is a scaled down version of Curiosity rover and uses a Raspberry Pi as the control module, to encourage students and hobbyists to get involved in mechanical, software, electronics, and robotics engineering.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] There are a number of developers and applications that are using the Raspberry Pi for home automation.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] These programmers are making an effort to modify the Raspberry Pi into a cost-affordable solution in energy monitoring and power consumption.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Because of the relatively low cost of the Raspberry Pi, this has become a popular and economical alternative to the more expensive commercial solutions.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In June 2014, Polish industrial automation manufacturer TECHBASE released ModBerry, an industrial computer based on the Raspberry Pi Compute Module.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The device has a number of interfaces, most notably RS-485/232 serial ports, digital and analogue inputs/outputs, CAN and economical 1-Wire buses, all of which are widely used in the automation industry.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The design allows the use of the Compute Module in harsh industrial environments, leading to the conclusion that the Raspberry Pi is no longer limited to home and science projects, but can be widely used as an Industrial IoT solution and achieve goals of Industry 4.0.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In March 2018, SUSE announced commercial support for SUSE Linux Enterprise on the Raspberry Pi 3 Model B to support a number of undisclosed customers implementing industrial monitoring with the Raspberry Pi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In January 2021, TECHBASE announced a Raspberry Pi Compute Module 4 cluster for AI accelerator, routing and file server use.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The device contains one or more standard Raspberry Pi Compute Module 4s in an industrial DIN rail housing, with some versions containing one or more Coral Edge tensor processing units.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The Organelle is a portable synthesiser, a sampler, a sequencer, and an effects processor designed and assembled by Critter & Guitari.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] It incorporates a Raspberry Pi computer module running Linux.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Slice is a digital media player which also uses a Compute Module as its heart.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] It was crowd-funded in an August 2014 Kickstarter campaign.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The software running on Slice is based on Kodi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Numerous commercial thin client computer terminals use the Raspberry Pi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, demand increased primarily due to the increase in remote work, but also because of the use of many Raspberry Pi Zeros in ventilators for COVID-19 patients in countries such as Colombia, which were used to combat strain on the healthcare system.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In March 2020, Raspberry Pi sales reached 640,000 units, the second largest month of sales in the company's history.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The Iranian Geran-5 aerial drone is reportedly built around a Raspberry Pi.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The **Astro Pi** project was launched in December 2014 at an event held by the UK Space Agency.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Astro Pi units are augmented Raspberry Pi computers equipped with a Sensor HAT and either a visible-light or infrared camera.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The associated competition, called *Principia*, opened in January 2015 to primary and secondary school students in the United Kingdom.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] During his mission, British European Space Agency astronaut Tim Peake deployed the computers aboard the International Space Station.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] He executed the winning student programs in orbit, collected the resulting data, and transmitted it to Earth for distribution to the teams.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Competition themes included spacecraft sensors, satellite imaging, space measurements, data fusion, and space radiation.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] Organisations involved in the Astro Pi initiative include the UK Space Agency, UKspace, the Raspberry Pi Foundation, ESERO-UK, and the European Space Agency (ESA).
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In 2017, ESA expanded the programme with a Europe-wide competition, *Proxima*, open to students across the European Union.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] The winning programs were run on the ISS by French astronaut Thomas Pesquet.
[src:raspberry-pi/raspberry-pi-p02] In December 2021, another pair of Astro Pi units were launched aboard a SpaceX Dragon 2 spacecraft.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] Announced on 21 January 2021, the RP2040 is the first microcontroller designed by Raspberry Pi Ltd.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] The microcontroller is low cost, with the Raspberry Pi Pico being introduced at US$4 and the RP2040 itself costing US$1.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] The microcontroller can be programmed in assembly, C, C++, Forth, Swift, Free Pascal, Rust, Go, MicroPython, CircuitPython, PicoRuby, Ada, TypeScript and Zig.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] It is powerful enough to run TensorFlow Lite.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] At announcement time, four other manufacturers (Adafruit, Pimoroni, Arduino, SparkFun) were at advanced stages of their product design, awaiting the widespread availability of chips to be put into production.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] Hackaday notes the benefits of the RP2040 as being from Raspberry Pi, having a good feature set, and being released in low-cost packages.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] Multiple stepping levels of the chip have been produced.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] The RP2040 chip is a 7-by-7-millimetre (0.28 in × 0.28 in) QFN-56EP surface-mount device (SMD) package manufactured by TSMC using its 40 nm process.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] For comparison with the RP2350, see RP2350 § Family comparison.
[src:raspberry-pi/rp2040] A number of manufacturers have announced their own boards using the RP2040.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] A **single-board computer** (**SBC**) is a complete computer built on a single circuit board, with microprocessor(s), memory, input/output (I/O) and other features required of a functional computer.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers are commonly made as demonstration or development systems, for educational systems, or for use as embedded computer controllers.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Many types of home computers or portable computers integrate all their functions onto a single printed circuit board.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Unlike a desktop personal computer, single-board computers often do not rely on expansion slots for peripheral functions or expansion.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers have been built using a wide range of microprocessors.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Simple designs, such as those built by computer hobbyists, often use static RAM and low-cost 32- or 64-bit processors like ARM.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Other types, such as blade servers, would perform similar to a server computer, only in a more compact format.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] A computer-on-module is a type of single-board computer made to plug into a carrier board, baseboard, or backplane for system expansion.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] It did not take long after the first microprocessors to arrive on the market before the first single-board computers arrived, for instance Intel's own SIM4-01 and SIM8-01 development boards from 1971 and 1972 respectively.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The SIM8-01 board is based on the Intel 8008 and contains a CPU, RAM, ROM, and a TTY terminal interface.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] It features 1K byte of RAM in 32 P1101A chips and 2K bytes of EPROM in eight C1701 chips.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The SIM8-01 has input and output capabilities in the form of a serial port for an external terminal, and it can be argued that this is the first true single-board computer in that sense.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Following a similar concept with CPU/RAM/ROM and a terminal interface, there was the Intel 8080-based MYCRO-1 released in December 1974, and both the Intel SDK-80 and the Motorola MEK6800D1 of 1975.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] A cheaper and subsequently more popular single-board computer, the KIM-1 based on the MOS 6502, would be announced later in 1975 and released in 1976.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Early SBCs figured heavily in the early history of home computers, such as the Acorn Electron and the BBC Micro, also developed by Acorn.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Other typical early single-board computers like the KIM-1 were often shipped without enclosure, which had to be added by the owner.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Other early examples are the Ferguson Big Board, the Ampro Little Board, and the Nascom.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Many home computers in the 1980s were single-board computers, with some even encouraging owners to solder upgraded components directly to pre-marked points on the board.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] As the PC became more prevalent, SBCs decreased in market share due to their low extensibility.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Computers began to move back towards fewer boards in the 2000s.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] As new standards like USB dramatically reduced the variety of peripheral standards motherboards were expected to support, advances in integrated circuit manufacturing provided new chipsets which could provide the functionality of many daughterboards, particularly I/O, in a single chip.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] By the end of the decade, PC motherboards offered on-board support for disk drives including IDE, SATA, NVMe, RAID, integrated GPU, Ethernet, and traditional I/O such as serial port and parallel port, USB, and keyboard/mouse support.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Plug-in "cards" retained their importance as high performance components, such as physically large and complex graphics coprocessors, high-end RAID controllers, and specialized I/O cards such as data acquisition and DSP boards.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The 2010s were defined by rapid and sustained growth in single-board computers, enabled largely by advances in integrated circuit production techniques that made it possible for the first time to include most or all of the core components of a motherboard on a single integrated circuit die.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] One of the more well known single-board-computers of the decade was the Raspberry Pi, which was built around a custom Broadcom SoC with open-source drivers.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Both of these factors dramatically increased production of single-board computers throughout the decade.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] By the end of the 2010s and the early 2020s, many devices, including smartphones, tablet computers, laptops and other smart devices, are powered by single-board computers which utilize advanced SoCs (System on a Chip).
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] While this has greatly increased performance and power efficiency, it has raised concerns that single-board computers, particularly those built around SoCs, are harder to repair and may be less friendly to attempts to monitor or modify instructions programmed into the boards by manufacturers.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers were made possible by increasing the density of integrated circuits.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] A single-board configuration reduces a system's overall cost, by reducing the number of circuit boards required, and by eliminating connectors and bus driver circuits that would otherwise be used.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] By putting all the functions on one board, a smaller overall system can be obtained, for example, as in notebook computers.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Connectors are a frequent source of reliability problems, so a single-board system eliminates these problems.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers are now commonly defined across two distinct architectures: no slots and slot support.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Embedded SBCs are units providing all the required I/O with no provision for plug-in cards.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Applications are typically gaming (slot machines, video poker), kiosk, and machine control automation.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Embedded SBCs are much smaller than the ATX-type motherboard found in PCs, and provide an I/O mix more targeted to an industrial application, such as on-board digital and analog I/O, on-board bootable flash memory (eliminating the need for a disk drive), no video, etc.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The term *single-board computer* now generally applies to an architecture where the single-board computer is plugged into a backplane to provide for I/O cards.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] In the case of PC104, the bus is not a backplane in the traditional sense but is a series of pin connectors allowing I/O boards to be stacked.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers are most commonly used in industrial situations where they are used in rackmount format for process control or embedded within other devices to provide control and interfacing.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] They are used in deep-sea exploration on the ALICE deep sea probes and in outer space, on the Ariane and Pegasus rockets and Space Shuttle.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Because of the very high levels of integration, reduced component counts and reduced connector counts, SBCs are often smaller, lighter, more power efficient and more reliable than comparable multi-board computers.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The primary advantage of an ATX motherboard as compared to an SBC is cost.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Motherboards are manufactured by the millions for the consumer and office markets allowing tremendous economies of scale.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Single-board computers are a market niche and are manufactured less often and at a higher cost.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Motherboards and SBCs now offer similar levels of feature integration meaning that a motherboard failure in either standard will require equivalent replacement.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Ranges of single-board computers include Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, LattePanda, Nano Pi, ODROID, Orange Pi, PINE64, and Banana Pi.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] One common variety of single-board computer uses standardized computer form factors intended for use in a backplane enclosure.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Some of these types are CompactPCI, PXI, VMEbus, VXI, and PICMG.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] SBCs have been built around various internal processing structures including the Intel architecture, multiprocessing architectures, and lower power processing systems like RISC and SPARC.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] In the Intel PC world, the intelligence and interface/control circuitry is placed on a plug-in board that is then inserted into a passive (or active) backplane.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] The result is similar to having a system built with a motherboard, except that the backplane determines the slot configuration.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Backplanes are available with a mix of slots (ISA, PCI, PCI-X, PCI-Express, etc.), usually totaling 20 or fewer, meaning it will fit in a 19" rackmount enclosure (17" wide chassis).
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Some single-board computers have connectors that allow a stack of circuit boards, each containing expansion hardware, to be assembled without a traditional backplane.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Examples of stacking SBC form factors include PC/104, PC/104-*Plus*, PCI-104, EPIC, and EBX; these systems are commonly available for use in embedded control systems.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Stack-type SBCs often have memory provided on plug-cards such as SIMMs and DIMMs.
[src:raspberry-pi/single-board-computer] Hard drive circuit boards are also not counted for determining if a computer is an SBC or not for two reasons, firstly because the HDD is regarded as a single block storage unit, and secondly because the SBC may not require a hard drive at all as most can be booted from their network connections.
